# Governance files — conventions

These files were generated by **guardrail**. When editing them:

## Branch + commit format

- Branch prefixes: `feat/` `fix/` `chore/` `docs/` `test/`
  `refactor/` `perf/` `ci/` `build/` `style/` `revert/`.
- PR title: Conventional Commits, e.g. `chore(governance): tighten
  CODEOWNERS for auth paths`.
- Every commit must be DCO sign-off (`git commit -s`) AND SSH/GPG
  signed (so it shows "Verified" on GitHub).

## Files you usually touch

- `CODEOWNERS` — when a security-critical path appears (auth, crypto,
  any file that handles user data), add it with the project lead as
  reviewer.
- `CHANGELOG.md` — every notable user-facing change goes under
  `[Unreleased]`. Cut a release by moving it under a versioned heading.
- `NOTICE` — when a new runtime dependency is added, append it to the
  third-party attributions list (with its license).

## Files you should rarely touch

- `LICENSE` — only via `guardrail apply --license=<X> --force`.
- `CODE_OF_CONDUCT.md` — based on Contributor Covenant 2.1; don't
  edit unless adapting for a special audience.
- `TRADEMARK.md` — read it before any change; brand policy decisions.
- `.github/workflows/dco.yml`, `lint.yml`, `auto-merge-dependabot.yml`
  — fixes here should usually go upstream into guardrail itself.

## What to do when a workflow check fails

- `DCO sign-off` failed → the commit is missing `Signed-off-by:`. Fix
  with `git commit --amend --signoff` or `git rebase --signoff
  HEAD~N`.
- `Conventional commit titles` failed → fix the PR title to match
  `type(scope): summary`. Bot-authored PRs (Dependabot) auto-skip.
- `Pre-commit secret scan (gitleaks)` failed → a secret leaked into
  the diff. Rotate the secret, then rewrite history to remove it.
